90. the Adaerb. The colloquial use oi intensive adverbs isone of the rnost striking stylistic peculiarities oi the Letters In this respect the language of Cicero's corre- spondence is even more remarkable than that of Roman comedy or satire. The adverbs which are used most fre- quently with an intensive force are bene, male, misere, nimia, perquam, pulchre, qaam, sane, sane qaam, satis, valeti, valde qaam, and veliementer, eg. bene magna (C. Cassius, Fam. 12. 13. 4), misere nolle (C. CassiuS,Fam.12. 12. 3), pulchre intellegere (Brutus and Cassius Fam. 11. 3. 3), sane quam sum gavisus (D. BrutuS, Fam. 11. 13. 4), and ve- kemenier four times (Cicero filias, Fam. 16. 21). Cf. also Index to the Notes under male, sane, etc.

91. The Prepesitian. Deis used very frequently to intra duce a new topic, eg. de mandatis quael tibi carae suit, est miti gratam (Cicero silias, Fam. 16. 21. 8).
